\f0\fs26 \cf0 As in archaea, the SECIS element is found in the 3'UTR of the RNA. Being in an untranslated region, it is not under encoding constraints. Yet, it has been shown that factors interacting with the SECIS recognize non-Watson-Crick base pair associations in the stem \{Walczak et al., 1998, RNA, 4, 74-84\}. The apparent importance of this primary structure actually drives the secondary structure (Figure <$n:figure:>). Indeed, thanks to those non-canonical base pair associations, the stem of the SECIS adopts a particular shape essential for the binding of specific factors \{Allmang et al., 2009, Biochim Biophys Acta, 1790, 1415-23\}. The fact that the SECIS is not located near the Sec-UGA suggests a very complex and tightly regulated mechanism to insert Sec at the right position. In this situation, EF\sub Sec\nosupersub  cannot directly bind to both the SECIS element and the RNA at the location of the Sec-UGA. Instead, it is recruited by SECIS binding protein 2 (SBP2) (Figure <$n:figure:eukSecInsertion>), which binds to both the SECIS and the ribosome \{Allmang et al., 2009, Biochim Biophys Acta, 1790, 1415-23\}. How exactly the SECIS/SBP2 complex recognizes a Sec-UGA is not fully understood. However, speculations can be made about the local context around the Sec-UGA, with some pattern driving the SECIS/SBP2 localization at the site of a Sec-UGA. We can also think that SBP2 binds the SECIS and the ribosome from the very beginning of the translation, recruits EF\sub Sec\nosupersub , thus preventing the ribosome from being released when a UGA is encountered. But then remains the question of how and under what conditions SBP2 would release EF\sub Sec\nosupersub , leading to ribosome release at the next UGA codon. Other data suggest that a viral RNA encoding for GPx4 possesses a SECIS element downstream of the UGA, in the coding sequence, and that it could be expressed in mammalian cells \{Allmang et al., 2009, Biochim Biophys Acta, 1790, 1415-23; Mix et al., 2007, Nucleic Acids Res, 35, 414-23\}. This raises the questions of how much specific the machinery of eukaryotes is, and what is the link between such apparently ancestral mechanism (until now specific to bacteria) and more complex ones.\
