\f0\i0 It is also worth noting that Sec synthesis in eukaryotes relies on SPS2, which is itself a selenoprotein \{Mix et al., 2007, Nucleic Acids Res, 35, 414-23\}. Although it has the same role as SelD (SPS) in bacteria, an homologue called SPS1 is present, containing either a threonine or an arginine \{Allmang et al., 2009, Biochim Biophys Acta, 1790, 1415-23; Chapple and Guigo, 2008, PLoS ONE\}. SPS1 does not seem to play a role in selenoprotein synthesis, though, but is essential for the viability of the organisms , and has been shown to be implicated in developmental processes in drosophila \{Alsina et al., 1998, Mol Gen Genet, 257, 113-23; Morey et al., 2001, Dev Biol, 238, 145-56\}.\
The size of selenoproteomes varies greatly among eukaryotes \{Lobanov et al., 2009, Biochim Biophys Acta\}. It seems that the largest ones are those of aquatic organisms, whether they are plants (algae) or animals \{Lobanov et al., 2007, Genome Biol, 8, R198\}. In fact, the zebra fish D.rerio is thought to all the vertebrate selenoproteome, with 19 characterized selenoproteins. It has been hypothesized that blue and green algae need an additional antioxidant protection provided by the selenoproteins. Furthermore, the high availability of Se in sea water could have made possible the integration of this element in oxidoreductase enzymes. An example of very scattered distribution among species is SelU. It is present in fishes, birds, and some unicellular organisms, but is present as a Cys-containing homologue in mammals and other eukaryotes \{Castellano et al., 2004, EMBO Rep, 5, 71-7\}. A recently characterized family, SelJ has also such a scattered distribution among eukaryotes and has been found only in actinopterigian fishes and sea urchins. \{Castellano et al., 2005, Proc Natl Acad Sci USA, 102, 16188-93\}.}